Google Trends to Nowcast UI

Paul Goldsmith-Pinkham + Aaron Sojourner

3/21/2020

Note: Data+code for this are available here https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1jlhCFX19FWZGVItv9j-9MB9L47p7Baf9jDzaNtT_jUY/edit?ts=5e74f03b#gid=0 and here https://github.com/paulgp/GoogleTrendsUINowcast

Goal

As the economy grinds to a halt, we want to know the aggregate and state-level initial unemployment insurance (UI) claims. However, the data on UI comes out with lags and in weekly intervals (typically with a lag of 5-6 days). We would like to forecast these these UI numbers (specifically, below, we would like to forecast the UI numbers for the week of 3/15/2020-3/21/2020). The preliminary official numbers for this will be announced on Thursday, March 26.

For the week of 3/15/2020-3/21/2020, we are greatly helped by many states reporting various numbers over the course of the week. The states partially released these numbers in press reports due the staggering growth in UI claims, with many states experiencing growth of 1000% or more. The first part of our approach gathers and harmonizes the various reported numbers across press reports to calculate an estimated weekly number. In many cases, this involves extrapolating to a weekly number based on one or two days of reported information.See our discussion below in the Data section for more details.

The second part of our approach imputes UI claims using data from Google Trends. We construct a dataset of the intensity of search for the term file for unemployment, state-by-state. We then compare the level of this measure for the days between 3/15/2020-3/20/2020 relative to the four week average four weeks before, and call this our Google Trends change. We regress this measure on the set of states where we have constructed a weekly growth rate using news reports, and use this to impute the initial claims for all states.

In the week of 3/22/2020-3/28/2020, we hope to forecast the UI claims rates using this model and the underlying Google trends data, once the data becomes available.

Summary of Results

We predict initial UI claims of between 3.25 and 3.3 million, depending on the exact specification. To put this in context, this change would imply a 2 percentage point increase in the unemployment rate in a single week. The range of our confidence intervals depends on certain assumptions, with our widest range include 2.2 million and 4 million, and our less conservative range between 3 million and 3.5 million.

Across states, we see large variation, with the largest growth in UI claims in states like New Hampshire, Rhode Island and North Carolina. The smallest growths were in Georgia, West Virgina and Tennessee.

Data Sources

News Sources

For the week of 3/15/2020-3/21/2020, we are greatly helped by many states reporting various numbers over the course of the week. The first part of our approach gathers and harmonizes the various reported numbers across press reports to calculate an estimated weekly number.

To measure weekly claims by state for the week March 15 to 21, we collect information from recent news reports on the number of new unemployment-insurance claims in each state. We found reports for 30 states. See this website for the data: https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1jlhCFX19FWZGVItv9j-9MB9L47p7Baf9jDzaNtT_jUY/edit?ts=5e74f03b#gid=0 Reports tend to describe the number of claims for a given set of dates (\(R\)) based on information from state officials.

We extrapolate this to measure claims for the whole week (\(C\)), differentiating only between week days and weekend days. Let \(D\) be the number of weekdays and \(E\) the number of weekend days represented in the report, \(C_D\) be the average number of claims on any weekdays, and \(C_E\) the average for a weekend day. Let their ratio be \(r \equiv C_E/C_D\), about which there is empirical uncertainty and variation across the few states in which it is observable. If observable, we use empirical \(r\) for the state. If not, we assume \(r=1/7\) and test for sensitivity.

Sets of reported dates come in three types. First, if only reports on weekdays are available, we compute a weekday rate and measure weekly claims as \(C = (5 + 2r) C_D\). Second, if weekend and weekdays are reported separately, \(C = 5\times C_D + 2\times C_E\). Third, if the report \(R\) contains information about total claims across both weekend and weekday dates but these are not separated, \(C = (5+2r) \times R/(D+Er)\).

Google Trends

We also pull data from http://www.google.com/trends, a Google product that aggregates search volume by geography. Many papers have used this previously as measures of activity one example is Stephens-Davidowitz (2014).

The data is unusually reported. To quote Google:

Search results are normalized to the time and location of a query by the following process: Each data point is divided by the total searches of the geography and time range it represents to compare relative popularity. Otherwise, places with the most search volume would always be ranked highest. The resulting numbers are then scaled on a range of 0 to 100 based on a topics proportion to all searches on all topics.

More specifically, to quote Seth Stephens-Davidowitz:

It (Google Trends) takes the percent of all searches that use that term; then divides by the highest number. So if 1 percent of searches include coronavirus in City A and 0.5 percent of searches include coronavirus in City B, city B will have a number half as high as City A.

We pull a dataset of all fifty states, collecting an index of the relative search volume for file for unemployment. A crucial feature of the Google Trends API is it is only possible to compare five locations per search. To elide this issue, we pull data for California plus four states, and continuously renormalize each state by \(\max{Index_{s}}/\max{Index_{CA}}\). This way, all states are relative to California (and now some of the index measures will be larger than 100.), and comparisons can be made both across time and geographies.

We pull data for all fifty states from January 18th to March 20th (the latest that the data is currently available). We plot the relative indices below, and see that similar to the UI growth in our news data, there is also substantial differences across states in the growth of the search term. Nevada experienced the largest growth overall, peaking on 3/18/2020.

Estimation

Finally, we consider the relationship between these two measures. For the states where we have used news sources to estimate weekly UI claims, we construct a growth measure, relative to the average 4 week claims between 2/22-3/14, the four weeks prior. We then consider the weekly average of our Google trends measure, measured from Sunday to Saturday (the same as UI claims). We consider the change in the index between the most recent week (3/15-3/20) and the average from the last four weeks (2/22-3/14). We plot this scatter and report the bivariate regression below.

We find an adjusted \(R^2\) of 0.22, which is remarkably good. We now use this model to predict the unemployment claims for the other states without data, and use this to aggregate.

Finally, we want to sum these values up to a single UI number. There are two ways to do this.

First, we can just use the predicted values, and ignore the news sources (assume that they were useful enough to calibrate our model). Given this assumption, we predict 3.3 million UI claims, with a 95% confidence interval of 2.4 million to 4.2 million.

Second, we assume that our news source estimates are true, and only incorporate the uncertainty / prediction for states we do not observe. In this case, we predict 3.25 million UI claims, with a 95% CI of 3.02 million and 3.48 million.
